						<aside id="description-2-7" class="sr-only">Three maps of the United States divided into National Climate Assessment regions use color shading and numbers to show the observed increases in hot and cold extremes in each region, as described in the caption. The left map shows changes in the number of hot days (days at or higher than 95 degrees Fahrenheit) per year. Legend values and colors range from decreases of 10 or more (dark blue) to increases of 10 or more (dark red). No numerical value or shading is given for Alaska. The Northwest, Southwest, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico show increases. All other regions show decreases. Numerical values for regional changes are as follows: Northeast, decrease of 1.3 days. Southeast, decrease of 9.7. Puerto Rico, increase of 1.0. Midwest, decrease of 5.6, Northern Great Plains, decrease of 4.4. Southern Great Plains, decrease of 8.3. Northwest, increase of 2.3. Southwest, increase of 5.5. Hawaii, increase of 0.4. The middle map shows changes in the number of cold days (days at or below 32 degrees) per year. The legend values and colors range from decreases of 10 or more (dark red) to increases of 10 or more (dark blue). No numerical value or shading is given for Hawaii and Puerto Rico. All other regions show increases except the Southeast, which shows a decrease. Numerical values are as follows: Northeast, decrease of 6.7 days. Southeast, increase of 3.0. Midwest, decrease of 4.9. Northern Great Plains, decrease of 4.8. Southern Great Plains, decrease of 0.7. Northwest, decrease of 10.4. Southwest, decrease of 10.2. Alaska, decrease of 10. The right map shows changes in the number of warm nights (nights at or above 70 degrees) per year. Legend values and colors range from decreases of 10 or more (dark blue) to increases of 10 or more (dark red). No numerical value or shading is given for Alaska. All other regions show increases except for the Northern Great Plains, which shows a small decrease. Numerical values are as follows: 