			<div style="padding-top:0.25em;">Alternative text
			<input class="clipboard-input-field tooltip" aria-label="Link to content alt text" data-title="Click to copy alt text to clipboard" type="text" value=" Four maps of the United States show the projected change in annual average precipitation at four global warming levels—1.5, 2, 3, and 4 degrees Celsius—as described in the text and caption. A legend shows change in annual average precipitation ranging from decreases of more than 20 percent (dark brown) to increases of more than 20 percent (dark green). At a global warming level of 1.5 degrees Celsius (2.7 degrees Fahrenheit; top left), precipitation is projected to increase by up to 5 percent across most of the contiguous United States and from 5 to 10 percent in the Great Lakes region and a small portion of central-western US. Increases in Alaska range from 5 to 10 percent in the south to up to 15 to 20 percent in the north. Decreases of up to 10 percent are projected in the south-central and southwestern portions of the contiguous US (abbreviated CONUS), as well as southern Florida and most of Hawaii, although the southern half of the Big Island shows increases. Most of Puerto Rico is expected to see decreases of 10 to 15 percent. Hatching indicates high model agreement for the decreases in Puerto Rico and parts of the Southwest and southern Texas. At global warming of 2 degrees Celsius (3.6 degrees Fahrenheit; top right), the area showing increases of up to 5 percent expands into most of Texas. The area with increases of 5 to 10 percent expands across the entire Midwest, most of the Northeast, the northwestern portion of the Southeast, and isolated areas of the central-western US. Most of Hawaii now shows increases of up to 5 or 10 percent. Alaska shows stronger increases, with much of the state showing changes of 15 to 20 percent, and more than 20 percent increases in the north. Decreases of up to 5 percent are shown across the southern tier of the western US, the tip of Texas, and southern Florida. Puerto Rico shows decreases of 10 to 15 percent. Most of the areas showing increases as well as the decreases in Puerto Rico have hatching indicating high model agreement. At global warming of 3 degrees Celsius (5.4 degrees Fahrenheit, bottom left), much of the northern two thirds of CONUS show increases of 5 to 10 percent, with a few areas in the north and central-western CONUS showing increases of 10 to 15 percent. All but the southern portion of Alaska shows increases of more than 20 percent. Decreases of up to 10 percent are seen in the southern Southwest and Southern Great Plains, and decreases of 15 to 20 percent are shown for Puerto Rico. All of Hawaii shows increases, with the Big Island mostly showing increases of 5 to 10 percent. Virtually all areas of increases plus Puerto Rico show hatching. At global warming of 4 degrees Celsius ( 7.2 degrees Fahrenheit, bottom right), most of the contiguous US is projected to see increases of up to 10 percent, with large areas of the northern Midwest, Northeast, and Northern Great Plains, as well as the Big Island of Hawaii, expecting increases of 10 to 15 percent. Alaska and high elevation areas in central-western CONUS show increases of more than 20 percent. Decreases of up to 10 percent are seen in the southern Southwest, Southern Great Plains, and the tip of Florida, while Puerto Rico shows decreases of more than 20 percent. Most of the northern two thirds of CONUS, Alaska, and Puerto Rico have hatching. " readonly/>
		</div>
	</div>


</div>


				<div style="width: 80%;" class="figure-inner">
						<a class="lightbox" href="/img/figure/figure2_10.jpg" data-title='Figure 2.10 Projected US Precipitation Changes at 1.5°C, 2°C, 3°C, and 4°C of Global Warming'>
							<picture>
		<source media="(min-width: 1200px)" srcset="/img/styles/figure2_10-1200.jpg, /img/styles/figure2_10-1200@2x.jpg 2x">
		<source media="(min-width: 992px)" srcset="/img/styles/figure2_10-992.jpg, /img/styles/figure2_10-992@2x.jpg 2x">
		<source media="(min-width: 768px)" srcset="/img/styles/figure2_10-768.jpg, /img/styles/figure2_10-768@2x.jpg 2x">
		<source media="(min-width: 480px)" srcset="/img/styles/figure2_10-480.jpg, /img/styles/figure2_10-480@2x.jpg 2x">
		<source media="(min-width: 320px)" srcset="/img/styles/figure2_10-320.jpg, /img/styles/figure2_10-320@2x.jpg 2x">

								<img src="/img/figure/figure2_10.jpg"
									 alt="Projected US Precipitation Changes at 1.5°C, 2°C, 3°C, and 4°C of Global Warming" 
									class="big-img img-fluid"  
									aria-describedby="description-2-10"
								/>
							</picture>
						</a>
						<aside id="description-2-10" class="sr-only">Four maps of the United States show the projected change in annual average precipitation at four global warming levels—1.5, 2, 3, and 4 degrees Celsius—as described in the text and caption. A legend shows change in annual average precipitation ranging from decreases of more than 20 percent (dark brown) to increases of more than 20 percent (dark green). At a global warming level of 1.5 degrees Celsius (2.7 degrees Fahrenheit; top left), precipitation is projected to increase by up to 5 percent across most of the contiguous United States and from 5 to 10 percent in the Great Lakes region and a small portion of central-western US. Increases in Alaska range from 5 to 10 percent in the south to up to 15 to 20 percent in the north. Decreases of up to 10 percent are projected in the south-central and southwestern portions of the contiguous US (abbreviated CONUS), as well as southern Florida and most of Hawaii, although the southern half of the Big Island shows increases. Most of Puerto Rico is expected to see decreases of 10 to 15 percent. Hatching indicates high model agreement for the decreases in Puerto Rico and parts of the Southwest and southern Texas. At global warming of 2 degrees Celsius (3.6 degrees Fahrenheit; top right), the area showing increases of up to 5 percent expands into most of Texas. The area with increases of 5 to 10 percent expands across the entire Midwest, most of the Northeast, the northwestern portion of the Southeast, and isolated areas of the central-western US. Most of Hawaii now shows increases of up to 5 or 10 percent. Alaska shows stronger increases, with much of the state showing changes of 15 to 20 percent, and more than 20 percent increases in the north. Decreases of up to 5 percent are shown across the southern tier of the western US, the tip of Texas, and southern Florida. Puerto Rico shows decreases of 10 to 15 percent. Most of the areas showing increases as well as the decreases in Puerto Rico have hatching indicating high model agreement. At global warming of 3 degrees Celsius (5.4 degrees Fahrenheit, bottom left), much of the northern two thirds of CONUS show increases of 5 to 10 percent, with a few areas in the north and central-western CONUS showing increases of 10 to 15 percent. All but the southern portion of Alaska shows increases of more than 20 percent. Decreases of up to 10 percent are seen in the southern Southwest and Southern Great Plains, and decreases of 15 to 20 percent are shown for Puerto Rico. All of Hawaii shows increases, with the Big Island mostly showing increases of 5 to 10 percent. Virtually all areas of increases plus Puerto Rico show hatching. At global warming of 4 degrees Celsius ( 7.2 degrees Fahrenheit, bottom right), most of the contiguous US is projected to see increases of up to 10 percent, with large areas of the northern Midwest, Northeast, and Northern Great Plains, as well as the Big Island of Hawaii, expecting increases of 10 to 15 percent. Alaska and high elevation areas in central-western CONUS show increases of more than 20 percent. Decreases of up to 10 percent are seen in the southern Southwest, Southern Great Plains, and the tip of Florida, while Puerto Rico shows decreases of more than 20 percent. Most of the northern two thirds of CONUS, Alaska, and Puerto Rico have hatching. </aside>
				</div>
				

					<div class="caption"
						 data-href="/img/figure/figure2_10.jpg"
						 data-title='Figure 2.10 Projected US Precipitation Changes at 1.5°C, 2°C, 3°C, and 4°C of Global Warming'>
						<div class="intent">Precipitation changes are projected to be larger at higher levels of warming.</div>
						<span class="ordinal">Figure 2.10. </span>These maps show projected changes in average annual precipitation (%) for various global warming levels (1.5°, 2.0°, 3.0°, and 4.0°C). Precipitation is projected to increase with warming in the North and East and to decrease in the Southwest and the Caribbean. Changes are relative to the period 1851–1900. Based on CMIP6. Data were not available for the US Affiliated Pacific Islands. Hatching indicates areas where 80% or more of the models agree on the sign of the change. Figure credit: Project Drawdown, Stripe Inc., NOAA NCEI, and CISESS NC.
					</div>
	    </section> 
 



<h3 id="the-risk-of-extreme-heat-increases-with-the-global-warming-level">The Risk of Extreme Heat Increases with the Global Warming Level</h3>
<p>Recent trends in extreme heat and precipitation foreshadow what is to come in a warmer world. The connection between warming and heatwaves is well understood: at the very basic level, as average temperatures warm, the risk of extreme temperatures and record-breaking temperatures goes up (Ch. <a target='_blank' href='/chapter/3'>3</a>), and it is <em>very likely</em> that heatwaves will increase in frequency, severity, and duration as warming continues. Figure <a target='_blank' href="#fig-2-11">2.11a</a> shows projected changes in the number of days at or above 95°F at a global warming level of 2°C. In addition to changes in the number of hot days, multiday heatwaves are <em>very likely</em> to last longer, affect a larger spatial extent, and become more severe, exposing more people and infrastructure simultaneously and for longer periods.<sup><a href="#fn:179" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">179</a></sup> By contrast, the number of cold days is projected to decrease (Figure <a target='_blank' href='/chapter/2#fig-2-11'>2.11b</a>). Nighttime temperatures are <em>very likely</em> to increase faster than daytime temperatures, leading to an increase in extreme nighttime temperatures as the global warming level increases (Figure <a target='_blank' href='/chapter/2#fig-2-11'>2.11c</a>). Such changes in extreme heat are <em>very likely</em> to have negative impacts on human health (Ch. <a target='_blank' href='/chapter/15'>15</a>) and agricultural productivity (Ch. <a target='_blank' href='/chapter/11'>11</a>).</p>



	
		<section id="fig-2-11" class="grid-col-12 tablet:grid-col-8 big-figure figure">

