<h3 id="the-frequency-and-severity-of-heavy-precipitation-increases-with-the-global-warming-level">The Frequency and Severity of Heavy Precipitation Increases with the Global Warming Level</h3>
<p>Extreme precipitation–producing weather systems ranging from tropical cyclones to atmospheric rivers are <em>very likely</em> to produce heavier precipitation at higher global warming levels.<sup><a href="#fn:127" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">127</a></sup><sup class="cm">,</sup><sup><a href="#fn:180" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">180</a></sup><sup class="cm">,</sup><sup><a href="#fn:181" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">181</a></sup><sup class="cm">,</sup><sup><a href="#fn:182" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">182</a></sup><sup class="cm">,</sup><sup><a href="#fn:183" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">183</a></sup> Recent increases in the frequency, severity, and amount of extreme precipitation are expected to continue across the US even if global warming is limited to Paris Agreement targets.<sup><a href="#fn:126" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">126</a></sup><sup class="cm">,</sup><sup><a href="#fn:184" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">184</a></sup> Figure <a target='_blank' href="#fig-2-12">2.12</a> shows <em>likely</em> changes at a GWL of 2°C. Changes in extreme precipitation events differ seasonally—they are <em>very likely</em> to increase in spring and winter across CONUS and Alaska and in eastern and northwestern states in the fall, while projected changes in the summer season are more uncertain.<sup><a href="#fn:185" rel="footnote" onclick="return false;">185</a></sup></p>



	
		<section id="fig-2-12" class="grid-col-12 tablet:grid-col-8 big-figure figure">

